{
    "title": "Barbados profile - Timeline",
    "link": "https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-18724156",
    "content": [
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "A chronology of key events:",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1536",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Portuguese explorer Pedro a Campos visits the island."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/448/mcs/media/images/62379000/jpg/_62379752_barbados_bridgetown_1910_g.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Bridgetown, pictured in 1910, was founded in 1628 as Indian Bridge"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1627",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Captain Henry Powell lands a party of English settlers who establish a colony, which they then develop as a sugar plantation economy using slaves brought in from Africa."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1639",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Barbados's first parliament, the House of Assembly, holds its first meeting."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1663",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Barbados is made into an English crown possession."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1816",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Slaves stage a revolt."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1834",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Slavery abolished."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1876",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- British proposal for a confederation of Barbados and the Windward Islands triggers bloody riots in Barbados."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Political parties formed",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/304/mcs/media/images/62379000/jpg/_62379754_barbados_police_g.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Barbados was a British colony until 1966"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1937 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Outbreak of riots in response to poor economic conditions; British Royal Commission sent in to investigate conditions; Barbados Labour Party (BLP) founded by Grantley Adams."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1951 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Universal adult suffrage introduced; BLP wins general elections."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1954 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Ministerial government set up with Grantley Adams as premier."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1955 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Democratic Labour Party (DLP) formed out of a splinter of the BLP."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1958-62 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Barbados a member of the British-sponsored Federation of the West Indies, of which Grantley Adams became the first prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1961 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Barbados granted full internal self-government with DLP leader Errol Barrow as premier."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Independence",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1966 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Barbados becomes independent with Barrow as prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1967 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Barbados joins the United Nations."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/448/mcs/media/images/62379000/jpg/_62379753_barbados_sugar_workers_g.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Sugar plantations, like this one pictured in 1910, form a major part of the economy"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1972 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Barbados establishes relations with Cuba."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1976 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "BLP, led by Tom Adams, the son of Grantley Adams, returns to power after winning the first general elections since 1961."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1983 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Barbados supports and provides a base for the US invasion of Grenada."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1985 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Adams dies and is replaced by Bernard St John (BLP) as prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1986 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Errol Barrow becomes prime minister after his DLP wins the general elections."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1987 -",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Erskine Lloyd Sandiford (DLP) becomes prime minister following the death of Barrow."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1994",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Owen Arthur becomes prime minister after his BLP wins a decisive victory in the general elections, securing 19 of the 28 seats in the House of Assembly, the lower chamber of parliament."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/304/mcs/media/images/62383000/jpg/_62383102_barbados-sugarcane-afp-gett.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Machines have replaced slaves on sugar estates"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1999",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- BLP wins a landslide in the general elections, capturing 26 of the 28 seats in the House of Assembly."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2002",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Barbados is removed from the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) list of countries deemed to be uncooperative tax havens. The country was put on the list in 2000."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2003",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "May - BLP wins 23 of 30 seats in general elections; Owen Arthur returned for third term."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Border disputes",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2004",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "February - Sea border disagreement with Trinidad and Tobago flares after arrest of Barbadian fishermen. Barbados takes border case to UN-backed tribunal."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2008",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "January - Parliamentary elections won by opposition Democratic Labour Party. David Thompson becomes prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2008",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - Launch of bid for offshore oil exploration leads to row with Venezuela over demarcation of maritime border."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2009",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - PM David Thompson survives no-confidence vote brought over his handling of financial crisis precipitated by collapse of Trinidad-based insurance company Clico - the region's biggest casualty of global financial crisis."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2010",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "October - Prime Minister Thompson dies in office. Freundel Stuart becomes PM."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2013",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "February - The governing Democratic Labour Party scores a narrow victory in parliamentary elections."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2014",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - The government announces plans to abolish the mandatory death penalty for murder. Executions have not been carried out since 1984."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2015",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "April - Australian mining giant BHP Billiton is granted licences to explore for oil in waters southeast of Barbados."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2015",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "December - Prime Minister Stuart announces plans to remove Queen Elizabeth II as the titular head of state and to make Barbados a republic."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2017",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "May - European Union finance ministers publish a list of seventeen jurisdictions, including Barbados, they accuse of being uncooperative on tax matters."
            ]
        }
    ]
}